# lychee link-checker ignore patterns
# Matched against full URLs. See https://lychee.cli.rs/#/usage/config for syntax.
#
# Add entries when a real URL 429s or rate-limits CI-side but is actually valid.
# Do NOT add entries for genuinely broken links — fix the link instead.

# GitHub issues / PRs that may not exist at check time (404 on dynamic paths
# is acceptable when the CI is run before the referenced PR is filed)
^https://github\.com/.*/(issues|pull|discussions)/new

# Microsoft documentation frequently returns 403 to unauthenticated IPs
# from cloud CI runners. The pages are real; access is geo-gated or
# UA-gated. Safe to ignore.
^https://learn\.microsoft\.com/
^https://docs\.microsoft\.com/

# Microsoft Download Center — individual download paths are reorganised
# without redirects (e.g. the httpPlatformHandler MSI moved silently,
# producing a 404 in run 25764379480). The host is stable but CI cannot
# reach most paths unauthenticated anyway. Same suppression pattern as
# learn.microsoft.com above.
^https://download\.microsoft\.com/

# Archive.org snapshots are occasionally slow/timeouts in CI
^https://web\.archive\.org/

# FedRAMP PMO site (fedramp.gov) returns 403 to unauthenticated cloud CI
# runners — same pattern as learn.microsoft.com above. The /resources/documents/
# and /rev5/documents-templates paths were also reorganized in the 2025 FedRAMP
# 20x relaunch and no longer resolve. Provenance tables and ADRs that cite these
# URLs are historical records, not navigable references. Fix live links manually
# if fedramp.gov ever provides stable, CI-accessible URLs.
^https://www\.fedramp\.gov/

# Anchor-only links within rendered Quarto pages that lychee resolves
# against fragments ('#section'); handled by quarto render, not lychee
^#

# Diagram pipeline patterns
^file://
\.mmd$
UIAO-DIAGRAM
UIAO-INJECT


# Archived pre-split monorepo (WhalerMike/uiao-core was removed after the
# four-repo consolidation into WhalerMike/uiao). Issue/PR/discussion URLs in
# CHANGELOG.md and ADRs are historical provenance records, not navigable links.
^https://github\.com/WhalerMike/uiao-core/

# GitHub profile that no longer exists (referenced in core/CHANGELOG.md).
^https://github\.com/endgantt\b

# Cisco documentation — URL restructuring caused 404s on the SD-WAN router
# series page referenced in docs/docs/vendor_stack_v1.0.qmd.
# Cisco reorganises /c/en/us/support/ paths without redirects.
^https://www\.cisco\.com/

# Microsoft Graph API endpoints appear as URLs in contributor setup docs but
# are not navigable web pages — they return 400/401/403 from unauthenticated
# cloud CI runners. Same suppression pattern as learn.microsoft.com above.
# .us is the Microsoft Graph host for the GCC High government cloud and
# is referenced in the customer-doc Intune policy templates.
^https://graph\.microsoft\.com/
^https://graph\.microsoft\.us/

# Microsoft Entra portal returns 403 to unauthenticated cloud CI runners.
# Same suppression pattern as learn.microsoft.com above.
^https://entra\.microsoft\.com/

# Claude.ai session/workspace URLs are authenticated per-user surfaces — they
# return 302/403 to unauthenticated cloud CI runners. They appear in
# inbox/ session-export markdown as nav chrome from the Claude web UI.
^https://claude\.ai/

# GitHub repository settings pages (secrets, actions, permissions) require
# admin auth and return 404 to unauthenticated cloud CI runners. They appear
# in session-log setup instructions as operator walk-through URLs.
^https://github\.com/WhalerMike/[^/]+/settings/

# Template URLs with unsubstituted shell variables. These appear as literal
# strings in contributor setup docs (e.g. contributor-tier-1-setup.qmd) where
# the reader is expected to substitute their own tenant ID before using them.
# Lychee tries to fetch the raw literal and the target service returns 4xx/5xx.
\$UIAO_[A-Z_]+

# json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/schema returns transient 503s under CI load.
# The URL is the canonical identifier for JSON Schema 2020-12 and is embedded
# as a reference in multiple canon + modernization docs — it does not need to
# resolve at check time.
^https://json-schema\.org/draft/2020-12/schema

# Internal example hostnames embedded in customer-facing docs (Gitea
# servers, doc portals, webhook receivers, CRL distribution points). They
# appear inside code blocks alongside fictional organizations like contoso
# and are never intended to resolve from CI runners. Without these the
# customer-document corpus floods the link checker with hundreds of
# unreachable .local / .contoso.* URLs.
^https?://[^/]+\.local(/|:|$)
^https?://[^/]+\.contoso\.(com|local)(/|:|$)
^https?://crl\.yourdomain\.com
# Generic internal-feed example host used in platform-server-build.qmd §0.5
# (Artifactory / Azure Artifacts mirror placeholder). Never resolvable from CI.
^https?://artifactory\.corp(/|:|$)

# Customer-doc code-block URLs that contain a literal PowerShell or shell
# variable expansion the reader is expected to substitute (e.g.
# $quartoVersion, $gitVersion, $(/$pr.number)). The unsubstituted template
# is not a valid fetch target. Generalises the narrower `\$UIAO_*` rule
# above, which is retained for documentation value.
\$[A-Za-z(]

# Microsoft Group Policy XML namespace URI — a literal xmlns declaration
# in policy export samples, not a fetchable resource. www.microsoft.com
# returns 404 for this path by design.
^http://www\.microsoft\.com/GroupPolicy/Settings/

# GitHub repository_dispatch endpoint — POST-only URL referenced in CI
# automation runbooks. GET returns 404, which is correct API behavior.
^https://api\.github\.com/repos/[^/]+/[^/]+/dispatches

# Mindcore Techblog (3rd-party blog reference in ADR-002 reference table) —
# host returns connection failure from CI cloud IPs but is a legitimate
# blog post when reachable. Cite stays for human readers; lychee skips.
^https://techblog\.dvbmedia\.net/

# TheTechTrails (3rd-party blog reference in ADR-003) — Google rate-limits
# the redirect chain into a 429 from cloud CI IPs. Same pattern as
# techblog.dvbmedia.net above; legitimate blog when reachable from a
# normal client.
^https?://(www\.)?thetechtrails\.com/

# Local dev-server URLs appear in contributor setup docs (e.g. quickstart,
# contributing) as walkthrough examples, not as live links. Generalises the
# `^http://localhost` exclusion already in the workflow's --exclude list.
^http://127\.0\.0\.1(:[0-9]+)?(/|$)

# piv.idmanagement.gov is referenced in the HRIT modernization proposed-canon
# notes. The federal host serves a TLS certificate valid only for
# coffa.gov / citizenscience.gov / fmi.gov / sftool.gov, so lychee correctly
# rejects it as a TLS mismatch. The misconfiguration is GSA-side; the URL
# stays as a citation for human readers, lychee skips it.
^https://piv\.idmanagement\.gov/

# Defense Counterintelligence and Security Agency (dcsa.mil) — referenced
# in the DCSA Clearance Attribute Service adapter spec and validation
# suite. Federal .mil host returns connection-failed from GitHub Actions
# cloud-IP runners (same geo-gating pattern as learn.microsoft.com and
# fedramp.gov above). The citation is a legitimate human-navigable
# reference; lychee should skip the reachability check.
^https://www\.dcsa\.mil/

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Azure / Microsoft API endpoints in code-block illustrations
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# All of these patterns are API endpoints that appear inside PowerShell or
# REST examples. They return 401/403/404 to unauthenticated cloud CI runners
# (which is correct API behavior — they require a bearer token), but the
# URLs themselves are stable Microsoft hosts. They are documentation, not
# navigable links, so lychee should not assert reachability.

# Azure Resource Manager — `management.azure.com` returns 401 without auth.
^https://management\.azure\.com/

# Microsoft Defender for Endpoint API — 401 without bearer token.
^https://api\.securitycenter\.microsoft\.com/

# Azure DevOps REST API — example URLs include literal {org}/{project}
# placeholders (URL-encoded as %7B/%7D) which 404 by design.
^https://dev\.azure\.com/

# Azure Instance Metadata Service — 169.254.169.254 is link-local and only
# resolvable from inside an Azure VM. Always fails from external CI runners.
^http://169\.254\.169\.254/

# Microsoft Entra OIDC discovery — templated URLs of the form
# https://login.microsoftonline.com/{domain}/v2.0/.well-known/...
# 400 because the {domain} placeholder is unsubstituted.
^https://login\.microsoftonline\.com/

# Power BI service-principal scope — `analysis.windows.net/powerbi/api/.default`
# is the OAuth scope identifier, not a fetchable URL.
^https://analysis\.windows\.net/

# Tenant-specific SharePoint Online hostnames — examples like
# contoso-my.sharepoint.com return TLS-mismatch errors from generic
# resolvers. Tenant SharePoint URLs are illustrative, not navigable.
^https?://[^/]+\.sharepoint\.com/

# Tenant-specific Azure Blob Storage hostnames — fictional storage accounts
# (e.g. orgpathguestconfig.blob.core.windows.net) appear in deployment
# samples and never resolve.
^https?://[^/]+\.blob\.core\.windows\.net/

# Templated raw.githubusercontent URLs with literal {org}/{repo} placeholders
# (URL-encoded %7B...%7D) — 400 by design.
^https://raw\.githubusercontent\.com/.*%7B

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Third-party API examples in narrative documentation
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Infoblox Cloud Services Portal — `csp.infoblox.com/api/ddi/v1` is the
# documented base URL for Infoblox DDI; returns 404 to unauthenticated GET
# (which is correct — it requires an authenticated session).
^https://csp\.infoblox\.com/

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Fictional internal hostnames used in customer-facing narratives
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# `wiki.internal` is a generic fictional intranet host used in incident
# response runbook examples. Same pattern as the .local and .contoso.*
# rules above.
^https?://wiki\.internal(/|:|$)
